01:10.547 --> 01:14.283
MAN: This is your mother?

01:14.384 --> 01:17.954
Is this her?

01:18.054 --> 01:20.056
Yes.

01:20.156 --> 01:22.592
And is this your father?

01:25.462 --> 01:27.730
I'm sorry, I have to ask.

01:31.000 --> 01:33.736
Do you know
how to sign your name, Clare?

01:33.836 --> 01:37.340
Or your initials?

01:37.440 --> 01:39.576
Right here.

01:58.327 --> 02:00.463
[Bell ringing]

02:04.367 --> 02:05.802
MIRA: Listen up, everyone.

02:05.902 --> 02:09.005
We have a new addition
to our family today.

02:09.104 --> 02:13.976
She's a very brave little girl,
just like every one of you.

02:14.076 --> 02:16.846
And I'm sure you all remember
your first day here,

02:16.946 --> 02:20.450
so I expect you to extend her
the same kindness

02:20.550 --> 02:23.386
you were shown.

02:23.486 --> 02:26.055
Take a seat, Clare, over there.

02:31.761 --> 02:35.598
MIRA: Now, I would like for you
to open your books to page 12.

02:37.099 --> 02:38.668
Spencer.

02:38.768 --> 02:40.069
Please read the first sentence
of number one.

02:40.169 --> 02:41.270
[Bell ringing]

02:41.370 --> 02:43.440
[Children shouting, clamoring]

02:49.345 --> 02:51.414
[Footsteps approaching]

02:53.416 --> 02:56.719
How come you're not outside
with the others?

03:09.065 --> 03:11.868
I want to go home.

03:13.703 --> 03:16.338
I'm afraid that's not possible.

03:16.439 --> 03:20.042
I miss my mom and dad.

03:24.947 --> 03:28.851
I wish I could tell you
they're coming back.

03:28.951 --> 03:32.855
But you're old enough now
to understand death.

03:32.955 --> 03:34.857
Its finality.

03:38.427 --> 03:42.298
The world is not
a nice place, Clare.

03:42.398 --> 03:45.134
You should know this by now.

03:51.508 --> 03:56.312
It's time to shed the skin
of your past.

03:56.412 --> 03:59.516
Grow a new one.

03:59.616 --> 04:02.051
Thick with anger.

04:04.086 --> 04:07.056
I don't know how.

04:07.156 --> 04:09.492
I watched a nature program
recently.

04:09.592 --> 04:12.061
It was very sad.

04:12.161 --> 04:13.530
It was about a gazelle

04:13.630 --> 04:15.965
who stayed on the fringes
of his pack,

04:16.065 --> 04:19.435
who was the first to be eaten
when the lion attacked.

04:19.536 --> 04:23.673
But the gazelle in the center,
who blended in,

04:23.773 --> 04:27.677
she lived the longest.

04:27.777 --> 04:30.412
And we need you, Clare,

04:30.513 --> 04:33.783
to live a good, long life.

04:39.589 --> 04:41.624
- You're it!
- [Children laughing]

04:47.930 --> 04:49.966
SPENCER [whispering]:
Shut that off.

04:53.903 --> 04:56.272
They'll never find us back here.

04:56.372 --> 04:58.941
[Children laughing in distance]

04:59.041 --> 05:01.778
I'm Spencer.

05:03.880 --> 05:05.314
[Whispering]
I like your braces.

05:05.414 --> 05:07.149
Really?

05:07.249 --> 05:09.118
Yeah, they're shiny and cool.

05:09.218 --> 05:11.654
I don't even need braces.

05:11.754 --> 05:13.656
My teeth aren't so crooked.

05:13.756 --> 05:15.291
So why do you wear them?

05:15.391 --> 05:17.560
Because my shadow wears them.

05:18.595 --> 05:20.529
What's a shadow?

05:20.630 --> 05:22.699
They haven't told you?

05:22.799 --> 05:25.101
GIRL: You're it.

05:25.201 --> 05:27.670
Come on, Clare.

05:27.770 --> 05:30.139
STUDENTS [reciting]:
On the other side of the door,

05:30.239 --> 05:32.508
I can be a different me.

05:32.609 --> 05:37.146
As smart and as brave,
as funny or as strong,

05:37.246 --> 05:40.049
- as a person could want to be.
- [Knocking on door]

05:44.887 --> 05:47.056
Clare? Come with me, please.

06:02.805 --> 06:06.175
[Heavy door closes]

06:06.275 --> 06:07.644
Where are you taking me?

06:07.744 --> 06:09.011
You'll be all right.

06:09.111 --> 06:11.347
[Beeping]

06:11.447 --> 06:13.015
[Lock clicks]

06:13.115 --> 06:15.051
[Door opens]

06:19.822 --> 06:21.557
Prep the anesthesia.

06:21.658 --> 06:23.225
MIRA: No.

06:23.325 --> 06:26.028
She must be kept conscious.

06:29.531 --> 06:32.835
What's happening?

06:32.935 --> 06:35.004
[Medical instrument clatters]

06:38.440 --> 06:41.110
Listen to me, dear.

06:41.210 --> 06:44.346
There's no easy way
to say this, but...

06:44.446 --> 06:49.151
we're going to have to break
your legs, and it will hurt.

06:49.251 --> 06:51.053
Badly.

06:58.060 --> 07:00.797
Is it because I wrote
in that library book?

07:05.267 --> 07:07.603
The hard part
will be over quickly.

07:07.704 --> 07:10.406
I promise.

07:10.506 --> 07:12.408
[Clare crying in distance]

07:20.349 --> 07:22.284
[Clare screams]

07:23.686 --> 07:25.788
[Knocking on door]

07:38.868 --> 07:40.970
How do you feel?

07:42.271 --> 07:45.842
I can't move my legs.

07:45.942 --> 07:48.110
You'll need to eat something.

07:48.210 --> 07:49.846
I'm not hungry.

07:49.946 --> 07:51.814
It's not about
being hungry, dear.

07:51.914 --> 07:53.850
I don't understand this.

07:53.950 --> 07:56.719
I don't know
what you're doing to me.

08:03.525 --> 08:06.128
Tell me what you see here.

08:08.530 --> 08:10.132
Me.

08:12.234 --> 08:14.837
My father.

08:16.705 --> 08:18.941
I've never been skiing before.

08:19.041 --> 08:22.644
How come I don't remember this?

08:22.745 --> 08:26.448
Because that girl
in these photos is not you.

08:26.548 --> 08:28.350
Of course it is, look at me.

08:39.861 --> 08:43.032
Ten years ago, something
happened to the world.

08:43.131 --> 08:45.835
And very few people
know about it.

08:47.536 --> 08:50.239
It copied itself.

08:50.339 --> 08:52.174
Split in two.

08:52.274 --> 08:55.011
Think of it like a door
you can walk through,

08:55.111 --> 08:57.646
and on the other side
is another world.

08:57.746 --> 09:01.350
With another me, another you.

09:01.450 --> 09:03.185
That's impossible.

09:03.285 --> 09:04.854
I'm not stupid.

09:04.954 --> 09:06.956
You said it yourself.
You've never been skiing.

09:07.056 --> 09:09.358
The people on the other side
look like us,

09:09.458 --> 09:11.127
act like us, sound like us,

09:11.227 --> 09:15.264
but do not mistake any of them
for the people you love.

09:15.364 --> 09:19.201
These people are the reason
your parents are dead.

09:20.602 --> 09:22.771
They died from the flu.

09:22.872 --> 09:27.509
They created that virus
to destroy us.

09:29.245 --> 09:31.147
[Mira sighs]

09:31.247 --> 09:32.348
Now, Clare...

09:34.216 --> 09:36.285
the reason
we had to break your legs

09:36.385 --> 09:40.923
is because the other Clare
broke them, too.

09:41.023 --> 09:43.092
And from this day forward,

09:43.192 --> 09:45.761
it's very important
that everything you do

09:45.862 --> 09:49.398
is very much the same
as everything she does.

09:49.498 --> 09:52.301
Why?

09:52.401 --> 09:54.770
Because someday, Clare,

09:54.871 --> 09:57.539
I don't know when,
but someday in your future,

09:57.639 --> 10:00.442
you will go to their world,

10:00.542 --> 10:03.345
and you are going to hurt them

10:03.445 --> 10:05.982
for everything they did
to your parents,

10:06.082 --> 10:10.486
and for everything
they did to us.

10:16.025 --> 10:17.994
<i>♪</i>

10:45.321 --> 10:48.224
<i>♪</i>

11:14.616 --> 11:16.618
<i>♪</i>

11:46.382 --> 11:48.750
CLARE: I laid out your clothes
on the bed.

11:48.850 --> 11:51.587
You should get in the shower.

11:55.491 --> 11:57.793
Is everything okay?

11:57.893 --> 12:00.296
You know how I feel
about birthdays.

12:00.396 --> 12:01.697
Please.

12:01.797 --> 12:04.066
You love being
center of attention.

12:04.166 --> 12:06.268
[Footsteps moving away]

12:28.957 --> 12:30.026
[Humidor creaks, closes]

12:30.126 --> 12:32.128
- Darling?
- Hmm?

12:32.228 --> 12:33.762
I just... my-my humidor
is completely empty.

12:33.862 --> 12:35.931
Oh, uh,

12:36.032 --> 12:37.599
- you have more in the basement.
- No.

12:37.699 --> 12:40.869
Not the Montecristo No. 2s,
t-the ones your dad likes.

12:40.969 --> 12:42.438
- Peter, I just put on the sauce.
- I'm sorry.

12:42.538 --> 12:43.872
I just have all this work
to finish.

12:43.972 --> 12:45.274
Would you-would you mind?

12:47.776 --> 12:49.011
[Sighs]

12:50.512 --> 12:52.881
If she wakes up,
she's your problem.

12:52.981 --> 12:55.017
Absolutely.

12:57.853 --> 12:59.355
Thank you, darling.

12:59.455 --> 13:02.558
CLARE: Take the sauce off
in 30 minutes.

13:05.727 --> 13:06.895
Maybe someone's been breaking in

13:06.995 --> 13:08.430
and stealing the documents
at night.

13:08.530 --> 13:10.966
Could be.

13:11.067 --> 13:13.001
QUAYLE: Could be the maids.
Could be...

13:13.102 --> 13:14.270
You know, it could be
the childcare.

13:14.370 --> 13:15.571
I mean, th-the-the leak
could be from...

13:15.671 --> 13:16.538
there's a number of different
people who could...

13:16.638 --> 13:19.541
You... C-Could you be a bit
careful, please?

13:19.641 --> 13:20.509
Look, we haven't got time
for this.

13:20.609 --> 13:22.344
She could be back
within the hour.

13:22.444 --> 13:25.147
- Bathroom in here?
- Yeah.

13:28.417 --> 13:30.152
This hers?

13:32.221 --> 13:35.191
QUAYLE: Yeah, it's fish oil.
She's into that.

13:52.007 --> 13:53.809
Smells like almonds.

13:53.909 --> 13:55.844
Cyanide, Peter.

13:55.944 --> 13:59.181
It's time we had a talk
about your wife.

14:01.417 --> 14:04.786
MAN: On the 21st of August,
she lost her last baby to it.

14:04.886 --> 14:07.389
Mr. and Mrs. Fancher placed
a silver heart necklace

14:07.489 --> 14:10.559
under her pillow
in place of a coin.

14:10.659 --> 14:13.129
Mrs. Fancher makes
Clare's lunch every morning.

14:13.229 --> 14:15.931
During her lunch period,
Clare often trades

14:16.031 --> 14:18.367
her potato crisp
for candy or sweets.

14:18.467 --> 14:20.869
Her favorite subject
in school is art.

14:20.969 --> 14:23.239
More specifically, watercolors.

14:23.339 --> 14:25.407
Her favorite color is pink.

14:25.507 --> 14:28.944
NEWSWOMAN: Villages on the
plateau were repeatedly assured

14:29.044 --> 14:31.480
there was little risk
of infection

14:31.580 --> 14:34.483
at their line of longitude,
but today's tragedy

14:34.583 --> 14:38.120
is another sign of the Munchen
Virus' growing strength.

14:38.220 --> 14:40.055
What's alarming
about the spread

14:40.156 --> 14:41.623
into the Balkan territories,

14:41.723 --> 14:44.160
despite German
border quarantines,

14:44.260 --> 14:46.628
is that every attempt
at containment

14:46.728 --> 14:48.530
thus far has failed.

14:48.630 --> 14:51.032
The death toll is rising
and continues to rise

14:51.133 --> 14:53.602
amid fear and panic.

14:53.702 --> 14:55.404
Meanwhile, the chancellor
is travelling back

14:55.504 --> 14:57.506
from the Cologne Conference.

14:57.606 --> 14:59.208
ALDUS: Her father is next
in line to run Diplomacy.

14:59.308 --> 15:01.109
She's not ready.

15:01.210 --> 15:03.479
We still have time.

15:03.579 --> 15:06.315
[Sighs]

15:06.415 --> 15:08.617
If we make waste
of this opportunity,

15:08.717 --> 15:11.587
it's on us, not the girl.

15:11.687 --> 15:13.489
We'll do it right.

15:19.561 --> 15:21.397
ALDUS:
Can you tell me something

15:21.497 --> 15:23.565
about her first week
back at school?

15:23.665 --> 15:27.636
I ran two kilometers
in 11 minutes,

15:27.736 --> 15:31.207
but then I ate too many
pretzels, so I threw up.

15:31.307 --> 15:33.975
Jaco gave me his soda
because he felt bad.

15:34.075 --> 15:36.545
And do you remember
Jaco's last name?

15:39.548 --> 15:40.782
Abelo?

15:40.882 --> 15:42.851
That's right.

15:42.951 --> 15:45.687
Very good.

15:47.856 --> 15:49.525
She doesn't do that.

16:03.905 --> 16:06.508
Very nice.

16:08.410 --> 16:10.111
Watch the line.

16:10.212 --> 16:12.214
Your Os are dipping.

16:23.992 --> 16:26.228
MIRA: Clare.

16:31.166 --> 16:33.502
What can I do for you?

16:33.602 --> 16:35.537
Do you know where Spencer is?

16:35.637 --> 16:38.974
Come. Sit.

16:57.192 --> 16:59.361
He has been called up,

16:59.461 --> 17:02.364
sent to the other side

17:02.464 --> 17:04.933
on a journey much like the one
you will take someday.

17:09.237 --> 17:10.939
When am I gonna see him again?

17:19.848 --> 17:21.317
You miss him.

17:26.087 --> 17:28.189
Those feelings are not yours
to have.

17:28.290 --> 17:29.725
Do you understand me?

17:29.825 --> 17:32.060
You're not some
stupid, little girl

17:32.160 --> 17:35.531
who gets to make friends and
boyfriends and hopes and dreams.

17:38.199 --> 17:41.403
You are a soldier.

17:41.503 --> 17:43.238
If that makes you angry,

17:43.339 --> 17:46.308
think of who took it from you
and focus on that.

17:56.217 --> 17:57.819
Congratulations.

17:59.921 --> 18:01.590
For what?

18:01.690 --> 18:04.726
You're truly suffering now.

18:04.826 --> 18:08.163
It's beautiful.

18:08.263 --> 18:10.031
It means you are growing.

18:17.673 --> 18:19.841
[Indistinct chatter]

18:19.941 --> 18:24.179
BOY: Hey, look what I got,
Terri. I found it in the yard.

18:24.279 --> 18:26.748
GIRL: Good night.

18:26.848 --> 18:28.216
Good night.

18:28.316 --> 18:31.687
- [Girls laughing]
- Good night.

18:31.787 --> 18:34.189
Can I borrow a copy
of Pride and Prejudice?

18:34.289 --> 18:36.725
[Indistinct conversation]

18:41.129 --> 18:43.699
GIRL 2: Does your shadow
have a brother and a sister?

18:43.799 --> 18:45.801
Does your shadow have a
brother and a sister?

18:46.635 --> 18:48.404
Does your shadow have a
brother and a sister?

18:52.608 --> 18:54.209
WOMAN: Lights out, girls.

18:54.309 --> 18:56.778
[Girls laughing]

18:59.715 --> 19:01.249
PRIME:
Where'd she go to college?

19:01.349 --> 19:05.487
Berlin University of the Arts.

19:05.587 --> 19:07.088
She studied architecture.

19:07.188 --> 19:09.024
What year did she graduate?

19:09.124 --> 19:13.429
Um... uh, 2006, 2007?

19:13.529 --> 19:15.163
Peter, come on. Focus.

19:15.263 --> 19:16.632
Details matter.

19:19.968 --> 19:21.403
Um...

19:21.503 --> 19:24.005
all right, she, um,
she was 24 when we met.

19:24.105 --> 19:25.874
My friend Toby introduced us.

19:25.974 --> 19:28.009
H-h-he was in Diplomacy.

19:28.109 --> 19:29.445
He used to work for her father.

19:29.545 --> 19:32.247
He... could he be...?

19:32.347 --> 19:34.249
Anything's possible.

19:34.349 --> 19:36.418
I'm sorry. It's ju...

19:36.518 --> 19:38.186
You don't know Clare.

19:38.286 --> 19:40.522
She's not like, she's...

19:40.622 --> 19:41.990
She wears cashmere.

19:42.090 --> 19:43.592
[laughing]: She's...

19:43.692 --> 19:44.993
She cooked poached salmon
for dinner.

19:45.093 --> 19:46.495
I mean, look at this place.
This-this is her.

19:46.595 --> 19:48.964
This whole thing. This is...

19:51.767 --> 19:53.368
Okay.

19:53.469 --> 19:56.838
If she is this...

19:56.938 --> 20:01.042
spy that we've been
looking for...

20:01.142 --> 20:03.044
- then she was raised on the other side...
- Yeah.

20:03.144 --> 20:05.447
Inserted into this life.

20:05.547 --> 20:08.016
So what happened
to my real wife?

20:11.152 --> 20:15.356
They might have been swapped out
years before you met.

20:15.457 --> 20:17.626
How-how do I know
which one I married?

20:17.726 --> 20:18.994
I guess you don't.

20:19.094 --> 20:20.696
Not for now.

20:22.698 --> 20:24.065
Does she know about your work?

20:24.165 --> 20:25.667
You think I breached
my security clearance?

20:25.767 --> 20:26.702
You think I've read her in?

20:26.802 --> 20:28.904
You bring paperwork home.

20:29.004 --> 20:31.507
Paperwork that every night
I put in my safe.

20:34.175 --> 20:35.744
What?

20:35.844 --> 20:40.381
The access code to my safe...

20:40.482 --> 20:42.651
is the same as the password
to my mobile.

20:42.751 --> 20:45.821
If she has access to the safe,
she has access to my phone.

20:45.921 --> 20:48.890
Fuck. God.

20:48.990 --> 20:52.360
She knows everywhere
you've been.

20:52.460 --> 20:54.029
That's how they found
the butcher.

20:54.129 --> 20:56.364
Yeah. Makes perfect sense
why they'd go to her.

20:56.464 --> 20:59.701
I'm fucked.

20:59.801 --> 21:02.170
I've had this job for years.

21:02.270 --> 21:04.906
We've been compromised
the entire time because of me.

21:05.006 --> 21:05.974
Listen.

21:06.074 --> 21:08.610
She's burned, all right?

21:08.710 --> 21:11.680
But she does not know
she's been burned.

21:11.780 --> 21:13.381
We have the upper hand
right now, okay?

21:13.481 --> 21:14.583
We can use this
to our advantage.

21:14.683 --> 21:16.952
We can find out
about her-her contacts,

21:17.052 --> 21:19.287
- her network.
- You-you-you-you want me,

21:19.387 --> 21:21.623
you want me to play along
with this?

21:21.723 --> 21:23.024
That's exactly what
we need to do, yeah.

21:23.124 --> 21:24.726
Like nothing's changed.

21:24.826 --> 21:27.428
Howard, I've got, I've got
guests about to come over.

21:27.529 --> 21:30.599
I've got people
from the office...

21:30.699 --> 21:33.101
You want me to knowingly
expose them to this?

21:33.201 --> 21:34.369
She's your wife, Peter.

21:34.469 --> 21:37.105
Just put on a smile

21:37.205 --> 21:39.340
and play the game.

21:39.440 --> 21:42.277
1996.

21:42.377 --> 21:45.413
Can anyone tell me why this year
was most important?

21:45.513 --> 21:48.049
Ethel?

21:48.149 --> 21:50.518
How should I know?

21:50.619 --> 21:52.821
I wasn't even born.

21:55.624 --> 21:57.458
The Crossing

21:57.559 --> 22:01.229
was first discovered
around 1987.

22:01.329 --> 22:02.964
But for years,

22:03.064 --> 22:07.168
our worlds were
almost identical.

22:07.268 --> 22:09.771
It wasn't until 1996,

22:09.871 --> 22:14.542
when their flu killed
millions of our people,

22:14.643 --> 22:17.178
that everything
became different.

22:17.278 --> 22:20.816
Now, who can tell me
some of these differences?

22:20.916 --> 22:21.917
Isabel.

22:22.017 --> 22:24.085
- Cigarettes.
- CLARE: Good.

22:24.185 --> 22:29.090
European countries outlawed
the sale of tobacco in 1999.

22:29.190 --> 22:31.827
Their phones are better.

22:31.927 --> 22:33.662
Yes, they've made
certain advancements

22:33.762 --> 22:35.631
we've been unable to make.

22:35.731 --> 22:37.666
And they still eat pork.

22:37.766 --> 22:39.334
STUDENTS: Ew.

22:39.434 --> 22:41.269
That's true.

22:41.369 --> 22:42.704
Their side didn't suffer
the virus

22:42.804 --> 22:44.640
that was passed
through our swine.

22:44.740 --> 22:47.609
In their world,
pigs still roam free.

22:47.709 --> 22:49.410
Anything else?

22:49.510 --> 22:51.613
[Bell rings]

22:53.915 --> 22:56.117
Ethel, stay behind, please.

23:02.557 --> 23:03.925
How are you?

23:04.025 --> 23:06.762
Like a Little
fucking Orphan Annie.

23:06.862 --> 23:10.065
I remember my first week here.

23:10.165 --> 23:12.734
- I didn't think I'd make it.
- Yeah.

23:12.834 --> 23:14.670
And look at you now.

23:24.012 --> 23:26.882
Let me give you a survival tip.

23:26.982 --> 23:30.085
Your attitude's gonna
drive people away.

23:30.185 --> 23:34.355
There's this documentary
about zebras.

23:34.455 --> 23:38.794
The ones protected by the pack
survive the migration,

23:38.894 --> 23:42.630
but the ones who hang out alone,
they're eaten first.

23:42.731 --> 23:44.565
Zebras?

23:44.666 --> 23:47.068
What the fuck are you
talking about?

23:59.147 --> 24:01.116
[Sighs]

24:01.216 --> 24:02.483
They're not always easy.

24:02.583 --> 24:04.986
Give me some time with her.

24:07.455 --> 24:10.425
What's wrong?

24:10.525 --> 24:14.429
MIRA: Apparently, he sprung it
on her during a vacation.

24:16.564 --> 24:18.166
She's marrying him?

24:18.266 --> 24:20.736
Her father put him on the
Director track in Strategy.

24:20.836 --> 24:22.704
Didn't want his daughter
marrying down.

24:22.804 --> 24:24.605
But they hardly know each other.

24:24.706 --> 24:27.342
Clare, I don't think you realize
what a gift we've been handed.

24:27.442 --> 24:29.878
A husband in Strategy.

24:29.978 --> 24:32.781
We've never placed
an operative that high.

24:36.284 --> 24:39.921
This has to happen now.

24:40.021 --> 24:42.690
Once he's been promoted,
he'll be vetted and monitored.

24:42.791 --> 24:45.426
It'll be harder
to place you then.

24:51.599 --> 24:54.836
You are going to be the one
who changes everything.

24:59.440 --> 25:01.642
There's a close friend of ours.

25:01.743 --> 25:05.814
He handles all matters of
transition on the other side.

25:10.685 --> 25:12.487
Hello, dear.

25:12.587 --> 25:15.690
I've heard so much about you.

25:15.791 --> 25:20.495
Mira tells me
you've been well prepared.

25:22.730 --> 25:25.033
We've manufactured
an identity for you

25:25.133 --> 25:27.335
under the name of Claudia Amin.

25:27.435 --> 25:29.737
You will be part

25:29.838 --> 25:32.941
of a diplomatic envoy.

25:33.041 --> 25:35.076
Our people will get you
to the Crossing,

25:35.176 --> 25:38.980
but once inside,
you'll be on your own.

25:39.080 --> 25:42.650
Purpose of trip, Ms. Amin?

25:42.750 --> 25:44.920
Embassy diplomatic support.

25:56.497 --> 25:58.466
<i>♪</i>

26:17.352 --> 26:19.254
